WEBVTT

00:00.930 --> 00:04.135
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:04.696 --> 00:18.376
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization, using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:19.117 --> 00:26.688
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:26.708 --> 00:27.890
Today,

00:27.970 --> 00:35.981
We invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:39.285 --> 00:40.367
Peace be with you, friends.

00:40.387 --> 00:51.802
We have a privilege this year because all souls day, November the 2nd, falls on a Sunday so we can really spend some time reflecting on this wonderful feast, which means a lot to Catholic people.

00:51.842 --> 00:57.650
I know all my years doing pastoral ministry, my years in the parish, all souls day means a lot.

00:58.210 --> 01:01.533
a time to pray for our beloved dead.

01:02.334 --> 01:05.918
And I wonder if I could begin by just reflecting a bit on soul.

01:05.998 --> 01:09.882
Why we speak of the soul, all souls day?

01:10.623 --> 01:15.208
Well, I go right back to the book of Genesis, the very beginning, that first account of creation.

01:16.089 --> 01:16.709
What do we find?

01:17.410 --> 01:23.516
We find that God makes Adam from the dust of the earth, from the mud, the clay of the earth.

01:24.317 --> 01:24.978
And then,

01:25.282 --> 01:32.029
breathes into him, like he's a mannequin or a doll, but then breathes into him the breath of life.

01:32.730 --> 01:37.255
And that word breath in Hebrew is one that's often translated as soul.

01:38.276 --> 01:41.680
But see what that poetic image is communicating.

01:42.541 --> 01:47.045
There's a dimension of us that belongs irreducibly to the earth.

01:48.147 --> 01:49.268
We are animals.

01:49.868 --> 01:52.091
We're close cousins to many animals.

01:52.131 --> 01:54.994
All living things are related to us.

01:55.202 --> 01:56.365
We come from the earth.

01:57.728 --> 02:00.655
Remember your dust and to dust you shall return.

02:01.798 --> 02:08.313
We have these emotions that we share with many of the animals and reactions and the nerves and muscles and all of that.

02:08.834 --> 02:12.242
We get hungry and thirsty and we get tired and we have to sleep and

02:12.706 --> 02:17.432
There's an earthiness about us that can't be denied, shouldn't be denied.

02:17.812 --> 02:20.256
It's part of God's creation, what God wanted.

02:20.296 --> 02:22.198
He didn't make us angels.

02:22.318 --> 02:23.299
He did make angels.

02:23.660 --> 02:25.262
They've got their own manner of being.

02:25.682 --> 02:32.131
But he made us precisely as earthlings as embodied realities.

02:33.292 --> 02:41.042
But that's not all we are because he breathed into these animal bodies

02:41.826 --> 02:42.627
the breath of life.

02:43.067 --> 02:45.691
Now, don't interpret that as this breath.

02:46.011 --> 02:51.357
I mean, what I'm taking now into my lungs, that belongs to my animal nature, my embodied nature.

02:51.998 --> 02:54.321
What's being communicated here is something more subtle, I think.

02:55.623 --> 03:02.411
God breathes something of His life and His manner of being into us.

03:02.951 --> 03:05.895
We're made indeed in His image and likeness.

03:06.315 --> 03:07.357
That doesn't mean our bodies.

03:07.417 --> 03:08.498
God doesn't have a body.

03:09.026 --> 03:10.888
So how are we in God's image and lightness?

03:10.909 --> 03:19.019
Well, we have in us this principle that links us to the immaterial.

03:21.683 --> 03:34.200
We're earthly, yes indeed, but there is something angelic in us, something higher, mind and will and freedom and creativity, religion, what connects us to sacred and holy things.

03:34.821 --> 03:35.922
We're a hybrid.

03:36.290 --> 03:37.171
We're a hybrid.

03:37.191 --> 03:38.393
We're embodied souls.

03:38.433 --> 03:39.715
We're in sold bodies.

03:39.735 --> 03:40.937
We're not one or the other.

03:41.578 --> 03:50.991
And can you see everybody up and down the centuries, there's a tendency to try to resolve this tension on one side or the other, to deny the spiritual dimension.

03:51.011 --> 03:52.754
That's what materialists today.

03:52.814 --> 03:55.077
No, we're just animals.

03:55.157 --> 03:55.939
That's all we are.

03:55.999 --> 03:58.282
We're sophisticated animals with bigger brains.

03:58.362 --> 04:00.525
And when we die, we die like animals.

04:00.545 --> 04:01.106
And that's it.

04:01.794 --> 04:09.765
And there are people across the centuries that kind of go the other way and say, no, we're basically we're souls and we're trapped inside these bodies.

04:09.785 --> 04:12.529
The idea is to get rid of the body as quickly as possible.

04:14.292 --> 04:24.306
I think much of the poetry and drama literature of the world is conditioned upon this dynamic that we're both body and soul.

04:24.578 --> 04:26.480
Look at Michelangelo's Sistine ceiling.

04:26.540 --> 04:37.793
I mean, you see the embodied quality for sure in those gorgeous depictions of the human form, but you also see on that ceiling the spiritual dynamic and dimension.

04:39.475 --> 04:47.804
Okay, the right resolution is not to emphasize one at the expense of the other, but to find the harmony between them.

04:48.525 --> 04:49.266
Now, I mentioned

04:49.890 --> 04:58.362
this tendency to over-spiritualize, see that in this whole platonic tradition, go right back to Plato, but comes up through the ages.

04:59.023 --> 05:03.469
The idea there is that the soul is kind of trapped in the body like a prisoner.

05:04.170 --> 05:10.618
And the point is to have a prison break is to get out of the body, get away from it, get up to the spiritual realm as quickly as you can.

05:10.638 --> 05:14.964
I think, as I say, it goes up and down the centuries, Gnosticism.

05:15.325 --> 05:19.090
The oldest heresy the church has fought is characterized by this.

05:19.714 --> 05:21.196
But you can see it today.

05:21.256 --> 05:23.559
Does this rhetoric sound familiar?

05:24.761 --> 05:28.346
Well, there's my body, you know, that was given to me at birth.

05:28.366 --> 05:30.289
But then there's the real me.

05:31.130 --> 05:35.476
There's the person I really am deep down and it's out of step with the body.

05:35.496 --> 05:39.481
And I want to remake my body to bring me in touch with the real me.

05:40.743 --> 05:41.344
Hey, hey, hey.

05:41.624 --> 05:42.846
That's not biblical talk.

05:42.866 --> 05:45.810
That's platonic, Gnostic talk.

05:46.530 --> 05:49.836
that the soul, the real me, is kind of buried deep down in there.

05:50.257 --> 05:51.980
The body is sort of at odds with it.

05:53.302 --> 05:54.725
That's not biblical anthropology.

05:55.667 --> 05:59.053
Look at St. Thomas Aquinas, my spiritual and intellectual hero.

05:59.974 --> 06:04.322
Thomas resisted the platonic understanding of the soul body relationship.

06:04.342 --> 06:05.544
He adopted Aristotle's.

06:06.306 --> 06:10.834
Aristotle said the soul is the first principle of life in a living thing.

06:12.002 --> 06:16.568
It's the form of the body, meaning not the physical contour of the body.

06:16.588 --> 06:28.784
It means the organizing principle of the body, that which makes this body truly human, the first principle of life in a living thing.

06:29.885 --> 06:33.430
Thomas says, for example, we're embodied creatures, yes, indeed.

06:34.010 --> 06:39.858
But we have a capacity to engage in sheer abstractions.

06:40.290 --> 06:43.318
Think of how the mind can know a number.

06:44.301 --> 06:47.048
I don't mean like looking around the world saying there are three things over there.

06:47.449 --> 06:50.738
But I mean when you have the number three in your mind,

06:50.882 --> 06:51.943
Now, make it more complex.

06:51.963 --> 06:55.228
You have an equation like three plus seven equals 10 in your mind.

06:55.448 --> 06:58.993
You're not looking at three things here or seven things there and then adding them up.

06:59.013 --> 07:01.817
No, no, you're grasping a sheer intelligibility.

07:02.237 --> 07:07.885
How about when you entertain the abstract notion of justice or of humanity or of truth?

07:08.305 --> 07:11.209
How about when you contemplate the quadratic formula?

07:11.650 --> 07:20.722
See, in all these ways, the mind is revealing its capacity to rise above the merely sensible, the merely perceptible,

07:22.114 --> 07:29.823
To the invisible, I like the idea that mathematics is itself a kind of opening of a door to the spiritual.

07:29.923 --> 07:30.744
Yeah, it sure is.

07:31.184 --> 07:31.645
It sure is.

07:33.106 --> 07:46.021
We're animals, uh-huh, but animals into whose body God has breathed this higher form, this higher capacity, called the soul.

07:47.222 --> 07:49.585
Okay, what's the upshot about?

07:49.605 --> 07:50.546
The upshot is,

07:51.170 --> 07:58.719
It's not true that when we die, we die just like a dog or like a horse or any other, any earthly creature.

08:00.121 --> 08:03.185
No, the body does indeed die, goes back to the earth.

08:04.647 --> 08:13.958
But this spiritual dimension of us survives, is not subject to death in the physical sense.

08:13.978 --> 08:20.466
And so we do indeed speak of souls, souls,

08:20.866 --> 08:24.191
that exists in the presence of God after life here on earth.

08:25.492 --> 08:35.045
Now, some of these souls are pure, ready completely to see God face to face.

08:35.766 --> 08:37.248
They're in heaven.

08:38.110 --> 08:39.171
We call them saints.

08:40.733 --> 08:42.035
And we have communion with them.

08:43.697 --> 08:50.066
You know, a saint for a Christian is not just a model of the spiritual life.

08:50.306 --> 08:53.130
someone who I read about and find inspiring.

08:54.251 --> 08:55.713
No, no, a saint is a friend.

08:57.556 --> 08:58.537
A saint's a companion.

08:59.519 --> 09:05.968
Listen now, existing in this higher spiritual world, but which impinges upon this world.

09:06.528 --> 09:11.916
It's not a platonic game we're playing here, whereby we escape from this lowly world to get as far away as possible.

09:11.996 --> 09:19.186
No, no, what we call the spiritual, just as my soul now impinges upon my body.

09:19.522 --> 09:20.984
influences my body.

09:21.465 --> 09:27.174
So the spiritual realm is in a way closer to us than we are to ourselves.

09:28.296 --> 09:32.343
In a way it contains touches upon the physical.

09:33.024 --> 09:35.388
And so we can reach out in our prayer.

09:36.269 --> 09:41.458
You know, Thomas Aquinas for me is not just a philosopher from long ago, theologian I admire.

09:41.998 --> 09:46.706
Aquinas is a friend who I talk to on a regular basis.

09:46.978 --> 09:48.099
communicate with them.

09:48.540 --> 09:53.827
I ask Him to intercede for me, so the saints in heaven.

09:54.448 --> 10:10.970
But then, let's be honest here, fellow sinners, most of us who die, even who die in friendship with Christ still aren't perfectly prepared to receive the beatific vision.

10:12.171 --> 10:14.354
Not because of any reluctance on God's part,

10:14.434 --> 10:16.877
God wants all of us to come to fullness of life.

10:17.378 --> 10:23.487
But we are, because of our sin, incapable of taking in that vision fully.

10:24.648 --> 10:25.389
What do we need?

10:26.411 --> 10:33.340
Well, the church speaks of purgatory, purgation, a sort of cleansing by fire.

10:33.380 --> 10:34.482
Now, don't literalize that.

10:34.522 --> 10:35.123
That's a symbol.

10:35.904 --> 10:43.314
Cleansing by fire means that something in us in our souls needs to be burned away.

10:43.938 --> 10:48.164
And painfully so, yeah, I mean, look at our lives here below.

10:48.805 --> 10:57.959
Whenever we try to rest ourselves away from the influence of some sinful form of life or we try to resist a temptation, it's painful, isn't it?

10:59.882 --> 11:07.954
Well, so in purgatory, we describe symbolically as a place of fire because it's a cleansing, it's a burning away.

11:09.016 --> 11:13.202
I want to give you kind of a gentler metaphor I learned from Cardinal George.

11:13.282 --> 11:14.083
my mentor.

11:14.924 --> 11:21.654
He said, imagine there's kids playing in a kind of a muddy backyard and they've gotten themselves all sweaty and dirty.

11:21.714 --> 11:25.219
And then the word comes through that their grandmother has arrived.

11:25.359 --> 11:26.000
A grandma's here.

11:26.040 --> 11:26.861
She wants to see you.

11:27.422 --> 11:34.773
But the kids' mothers say, all right, you can see the grandma, but you first have got to get yourselves cleaned up.

11:34.793 --> 11:38.458
You're not ready right now to receive her.

11:39.480 --> 11:41.202
And so the kids have to have to be

11:41.378 --> 11:44.322
and purified before they're ready for that encounter.

11:45.363 --> 11:49.369
You know, it's a different metaphor from the cleansing fire, but sort of the same idea.

11:50.350 --> 12:02.707
So do we recognize everybody that there are a lot of souls of people that we knew, souls over time, that are going through this pregation process?

12:04.048 --> 12:11.218
And therefore, is it appropriate for us to remember them, indeed, but more than that, to pray

12:11.362 --> 12:11.843
for them.

12:13.185 --> 12:14.447
Yup, absolutely.

12:15.268 --> 12:18.573
It's the best way we can stay in contact with them.

12:19.655 --> 12:22.078
I think of my mother and father.

12:22.479 --> 12:24.161
My father died many years ago.

12:24.181 --> 12:25.744
My mother just fairly recently.

12:26.966 --> 12:30.932
But I mean, all the time, I got pictures of them down in the kind of den in my house.

12:31.152 --> 12:35.058
And whenever I look at those pictures, I pray for them.

12:35.842 --> 12:41.369
Last year I was back in Chicago for a visit and I wasn't too far from the cemetery where they're both buried.

12:41.429 --> 12:45.013
I went over there and at their graves, of course I prayed for them.

12:45.033 --> 12:46.115
I didn't just remember them.

12:46.135 --> 12:47.036
I prayed for them.

12:48.318 --> 12:50.881
That's what all Souls Day is all about.

12:50.941 --> 12:53.965
So can I urge everybody today?

12:55.206 --> 13:02.275
Become consciously mindful of souls who've gone before us, people that you knew and loved.

13:03.556 --> 13:04.818
Don't just remember them.

13:04.962 --> 13:06.664
that's a good thing to do.

13:08.226 --> 13:09.068
But pray for them.

13:09.789 --> 13:13.514
And as you do it, realize they're not far away.

13:13.534 --> 13:19.642
I don't think of it as, well, here's earth and there's Jupiter is way far away and then there's some galaxy even further.

13:20.103 --> 13:21.585
No, that's physical distance.

13:21.605 --> 13:22.506
We're not talking about that.

13:23.287 --> 13:26.732
We're talking about a kind of qualitative difference.

13:26.792 --> 13:29.355
They're in a different place, so to speak.

13:30.277 --> 13:34.322
But not one that's far away from us, that we can

13:34.530 --> 13:37.374
access them through our prayer.

13:38.255 --> 13:55.740
And all souls day is the great day, at mass, as you pray, maybe even with your family after dinner tonight, spend some time, pray the rosary for souls who've gone before us, mark with the sign of faith.

13:56.521 --> 14:02.930
It's for those holy souls who long to be fully in the presence of God,

14:03.042 --> 14:06.427
whom we still love with the love of friendship.

14:08.050 --> 14:09.752
Reach out to them today in prayer.

14:10.594 --> 14:15.161
Ask the Lord to continue to purify them and bring them closer to Himself.

14:16.663 --> 14:17.244
And God bless you.

14:22.412 --> 14:26.018
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

14:26.398 --> 14:31.506
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire.org.

